I am not making that up, that is what that NBER paper says about the reason the recession ended so soon <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.philbrodieband.com/Slide13.JPG" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mithrilleyes>mithrilleyes</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.philbrodieband.com/Slide13.JPG" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 612<br> <font color=#333333>(4/17/05 5:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3301.topic&index=66>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Estate tax repeal pending in the house--grats Wealthfare</span><hr size=1> &gt;&gt;And then there's the ever-increasing bill<br>
<br>
Spending <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">increased</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> about 7-8% each year, during Clinton's term, or from 2% in 1992 to 10% in 2000. An average of $88 billion more each year. The maximum increase being $198 billion in 2000.<br>
<br>
Spending decreased from 10% in 2000 at the end of Clinton's term, to -1% in 2003. On average spending has <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">decreased</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> by 3% during Bush. That is an average decrease in spending of $63 billion a year, with a maximum decrease in 2002 of $138 billion.<br>
<br>
Revenues from taxes increased around 7% each year under Clinton. According to NBER economists this resulted mostly from the economic growth spurred by new technologies, and not from Clinton's tax increases, which in their view, actually reduced total revenues.<br>
<br>
In 2002 tax revenues dropped 300 billion <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">as a result of the recession</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->(there were no tax cuts yet), but only 150 billion in 2003 after tax cuts took place. That means that almost double the deficit amount incurred during Bush's term is the result of the recession  and not of tax cuts. According to NBER economist tax cuts helped end the recession faster.<br>
<br>
Finally, the idea that lowering taxes always reduces revenues is simply ignorant, and cannot be verified by historical tax rates when compared to revenues or growth. Until the 1970's, income tax rates climbed to nearly 91% for the higher brackets, around 40% for the middle class and around 20% for the bottom tier. Right before the Reagan Tax Act reform top rates were at 70%, middle at 40% and low at about 10%. Despite the high rates, revenues as a percent of GDP had remained at around the level since WWII, but the deficit steadily increased from 1948 to 1984. After Reagan's tax cuts, the GDP more than tripled, and that is without accounting for the reduction in inflation that also took place, which would make that number higher. Since then, the deficit has been declining as revenues have increased. If you look at a graph showing Federal Receipts and Outlays as a Percentage of GDP you will notice that, during the Clinton term, the deficit went up as a percent of GDP until the Republicans took over at which point it went back down. The reverse is true for revenues. When Clinton took office, revenues went down for a while, and then back up after the Republican take over. The current deficit as a percent of GDP is lower than most other years since WWII, except in 46-48, 69, 97-01. In fact, the deficit has only had surpluses less that 10 years total since WWII.<br>
It seems clear the solution is not raising taxes and increasing spending, but cutting spending and stimulating growth, which is exactly what is being done.<br>
<br>
<br>
(*) All data came from <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.taxfoundation.org/tfbooks.html">www.taxfoundation.org/tfbooks.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> . I calculated the % increases and decreases in Excel. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.philbrodieband.com/Slide13.JPG" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bumraz@ascension10244>Bumraz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1618<br> <font color=#333333>(4/17/05 9:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3301.topic&index=67>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Estate tax repeal pending in the house--grats Wealthfare</span><hr size=1> &quot;Bill&quot; in this context refers to Bush's love for deficit spending, even in the face of a growing economy. But you knew that.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;Spending increased about 7-8%<br>
<br>
Nominal dollar spending under Clinton increased at a rate of around 5%, while as a percentage of GDP it fell every year Clinton was in office.  <br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;In 2002 tax revenues dropped 300 billion as a result of the recession(there were no tax cuts yet)<br>
<br>
Bzzzt.  EGTRRA, otherwise known as the 2001 Bush tax cut, was signed in the middle of '01, and affected the 2001 tax year, and therefore, obviously receipts in 2002. Facts are your friend.  <br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;but the deficit steadily increased from 1948 to 1984<br>
<br>
More than a bit of a distortion.  The national debt's growth from the 40s to the early 80s was steady, but it was also modest, only actually doubling from 1962-1981.  Under Reagan, our debt nearly tripled. As a percentage of GDP, the national debt climbed from 25% at the start of Reagan's term, to over 40%, where essentially it's remained(cbo.gov historical budget data).<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;Finally, the idea that lowering taxes always reduces revenues is simply ignorant....<br>
<br>
Really?  Under Reagan, federal revenues as a percentage of GDP fell after his tax cuts, and didn't rise again until his &quot;revenue enhancements&quot; were passed, giving the feds access to new revenue streams (cbo.gov historical budget data).  After Bush's EGTRRA, tax revenue as a percentage of GDP has fallen and not recovered.  Your little truism only applies in recent memory when comparing later inflated nominal dollar figures, to prior nominal dollar figures.  At least from the CBOs numbers, when comparing as a percentage of GDP year over year--you seem to be full of shit.  Big surprise.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;When Clinton took office, revenues went down for a while<br>
<br>
Total horseshit.  As a percentage of GDP, federal revenues rose every year Clinton was in office, without exception.  (CBO.gov).  Further, the same is true for nominal dollar revenues.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;If you look at a graph showing Federal Receipts and Outlays as a Percentage of GDP you will notice that, during the Clinton term, the deficit went up as a percent of GDP until the Republicans took over at which point it went back down<br>
<br>
As a percentage of GDP, the debt and the deficit both declined *every* year Clinton was in office (CBO.gov).  <br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;The current deficit as a percent of GDP is lower than most other years since WWII, except in 46-48, 69, 97-01.<br>
<br>
That's just an out and out lie.  For the most recent year available from CBO, the deficit as a percentage of GDP was 3.6%.  This is higher than all but the very first year of Clinton's presidency, and other than that single year, the only other Presidents to equal Bush's record were Bush Sr. and Reagan (CBO.gov).<br>
<br>
I'm just astounded.  It's unlike you to make nearly an entire post that's completely factually inaccurate.  You didn't even make me work for this.  Have you been drinking? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bumraz@ascension10244>Bumraz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1619<br> <font color=#333333>(4/17/05 9:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3301.topic&index=68>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Estate tax repeal pending in the house--grats Wealthfare</span><hr size=1> Still further,  according to a report by the CBO on the AMT,  the AMT was owed by approximately 1 percent of taxpayers at the end of Clinton's term.  So while it may, in fact, have expanded under Clinton, to call that expansion significant, or to in any way compare what we're facing now, strains credulity.  1%&lt;30% (% of taxpayers  that will pay the AMT in 2011).  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bumraz@ascension10244>Bumraz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1620<br> <font color=#333333>(4/18/05 10:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3301.topic&index=69>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Estate tax repeal pending in the house--grats Wealthfare</span><hr size=1> &gt;&gt;&gt;The current deficit as a percent of GDP is lower than most other years since WWII, except in 46-48, 69, 97-01.<br>
