For the period for which the CBO publishes numbers, prior to Reagan, deficits averaged -1.6%. Under Reagan, deficits averaged just over -4% of GDP, nearly a 300% increase. By contrast, deficits under Clinton averaged -.76% of GDP.  Under Bush, so far, that's doubled to -1.8%. I've no reason to expect that the deficit will be less for '05. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=undinerz>UndineRZ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 58<br> <font color=#333333>(4/19/05 10:29 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3301.topic&index=71>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Estate tax repeal pending in the house--grats Wealthfare</span><hr size=1> I love skimming over each of your well thought out and researched posts.  Just think...if you guys all spent as much time trying to figure out how to make a fortune you could experience the tax bite first hand!  (And Bum..the mortgage business is not driven by the write off you get on your taxes, the driving force is usually either the desire to have your OWN home, or to create wealth through the appreciation of the property.)<br>
<br>
Taxation in today's market (in a nutshell):<br>
<br>
   -You're paid....you're taxed.  <br>
        1) Federal  (approx 33% min currently)<br>
        2) State/City  <br>
   -You buy clothes, food, furniture, cars....you're taxed  on    your taxed money. (6%)<br>
   -You buy gasoline....you're taxed on your taxed money.<br>
   -You go out to dinner/movies/date...you're taxed on the taxed money. (6%)<br>
   -God forbid you have the sense to invest...<br>
        1) You make a profit...you're taxed.<br>
   -You buy a home.....you're taxed. (1-3%)<br>
   -In some areas you buy a car....you're taxed annually. (1-3%)<br>
   -You're self-employed...you're taxed double (FICA)<br>
   -You die...you're taxed.*<br>
<br>
Now if someone that paid taxes on all this crap throughout their lifetime wants to give the money to their kids, why the hell shouldn't they?  If they don't want the kids to have the money, let them decide where to donate it.  <br>
<br>
I'll give you a specific example of how someone can inherit and still be admirable.  I have a good friend who's father made a ton of money on Wall Street.  My buddy is a good athlete and a great guy, but really isn't the sharpest tack in the box.  If he had to live on what he could generate himself I think he'd spend his entire life &quot;just getting by&quot;.  The character trait I admire of him is his recognition of his budgetary constraints.  He doesn't have a mortgage because he doesn't want to pay the interest, he has investments that increase in value.  He lives within his means and doesn't expect anyone else to pick up the slack.  His father through the inheritence created a self-sufficient, productive and happy member of the human race.<br>
<br>
If I'm picking a favorite charity then you can rest assured that the government is not at the top of the list.  <br>
<br>
*Tax rates are approximations based on Connecticut taxes.<br>
<br>
**All information enclosed is an approximate recreation...no proof sources will be cited....no further research will be undertaken.  <br>
