Traditionally Republicans have not been into &quot;growing government&quot;, however this focus has flip flopped a couple of times in the history of American politics with each party alternating their sad turn gorging at the public trough.<br>
<br>
What I would expect of a government that holds &quot;a very empty revenue bag&quot; is to reduce their expenses before they slop up to the trough again asking for more.  Unfortunately in this day and age our elected class is increasingly out of touch with reality with all the perks associated with the life of a member of congress.<br>
<br>
Given all that, you still don't address the points I made, which are we are being taxed at an ever increasing rate with no reason to believe it will stop.  When taxes on my house rise due to a reassessment does the government lower the mill rate so I don't pay a higher amount?  In affluent communities they do...in less affluent and traditionally democratic communities they take the surplus and spend it (plus a few hundred thousand) and increase the burden.  <br>
<br>
If you look back in history our parents and grandparents paid on average 13% for income tax.  That has now escalated to nearly 50% when everything is factored in.  If you look at the demographics of families we have increasingly become 2 income families paying someone else to raise our children.  That is a sad commentary on how the business of government is being run.....by BOTH parties.<br>
<br>
