Sorry, while no one wants to pay more than their share, but 50% is just not true. <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.rationalrevolution.net/articles/american_income_taxation.htm">www.rationalrevolution.ne...xation.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> has arguably the best treatment on this I've seen.  The reality is that while the wealthy pay more *income* taxes, but all the little taxes (fuel tax, property tax, cigarette tax, yada yada) for that selfsame group consume, proportionally, much less of their income. When all taxes are taken into account, tax rates in this country are roughly proportional to the amount of the income &quot;pie&quot; each earning  bracket receives.  There has been some shift of the tax burden away from the wealthy in the last 20 years, but it's not been huge, and has been mostly (and soon to be increasingly) borne by the middle and upper middle classes. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=symgharyl>Symgharyl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1412<br> <font color=#333333>(4/19/05 2:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3301.topic&index=75>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Estate tax repeal pending in the house--grats Wealthfare</span><hr size=1> If they just pass the Three Person Limit Kill law, this country would be out of debt and the best place in the world. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Symgharl Val`Sharess</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
